Textbook

Modern Industrial Organization

Course Description

  • This will be a full English course.

  • We will use English everywhere (textbook, slides, homework, exam etc.) except conversation.

  • Chinese homework and exam will not be accepted and get no score!

Course Description

  • Industrial Organization is study of firms and industries.
    • Using theory of the firm to examine structure of and boundaries between firms and markets
    • markets that deviate from the basic competitive model
      • transaction costs, limited information, barriers to entry

Course Description

  • Prominent topics will include oligopoly, cartel behavior, anti-competitive practices, price discrimination, and government regulation.

  • I like math but Ill try to keep it at a reasonable level

  • You could find the necessary materials in the course website: bayeswhu.github.io/teaching/io.html

  • You need to prepare to learn it by yourself and help each other.

Course Requirements

  • Homework
    • 1 Problem Sets
    • All homework should be typed (and stapled)
    • Work that is not typed (or stapled) gets an automatic discount of 30%
    • Assignments not turned in by the due date will be penalized 10 points for each day it is late
    • Students are strongly encouraged to work in groups. However, each student is responsible of writing up his or her own problem set.

Course Requirements

  • Exams
    • 1 final exam
    • Dates: April 13 2016, Wednesday
    • Any cheater will get a grade of zero. A stronger punishment is not ruled out.

Grading Policy

  • The weights for the final score will be as follows:
    • Problem sets: 30%
    • Final exam: 70%
  • I reserve the right to raise the final score, but I will not lower them.

Course Schedule

  • The material of the textbook is summarized below.
    • Part1: Introduction and Theory
    • Part2: Market Structure
    • Part3: Business Practices: Strategies & Conduct
    • Part4: Information, Advertising, and Disclosure
    • Part5: Dynamic Models and Market Clearing
    • Part6: Government Policies and Their Effects
  • We will definitely cover parts I, II and try to finish part III. And then, depends on time and your interest, I will try to cover more chapters.
